idCitation.resAltTitle: Gulf Islands National Seashore Vegetation Map

dataIdInfo.idPurp:
The Gulf Islands National Seashore (GUIS) vegetation inventory project was initiated by the National Park Service (NPS) Vegetation Mapping Inventory (VMI) Program. The goals of the vegetation mapping project were to adequately classify, describe, and map vegetation types of GUIS and provide resource managers, biological researchers, and the NPS Natural Resource Inventory and Monitoring (I&M) Program with useful baseline vegetation information. This vegetation information is to support a wide variety of resource assessment, park management, and planning needs, providing a structure for framing and answering critical scientific questions about vegetation communities and their relation to environmental processes across the landscape.
The Park administrative boundary consist of 52,750.0 hectares (ha) (130,348.1 acres (ac)). During scoping, it was decided that only the Park owned portions, excluding Fort Barrancas, of the seashore would be mapped under this project. The total mapped area for this project is 35,769.0 ha (88,387.2 ac), of which a vast majority is water/ocean. Only 4,455.5 ha (11,009.7 ac) is land area.
dataIdInfo.idAbs:
The NPS VMI Program is an effort to classify, describe, and map existing vegetation of national park units for the NPS Natural Resource I&M Program. The NPS VMI Program is managed by the NPS I&M Division and provides baseline vegetation information to the NPS Natural Resource I&M Program. The geographic information system (GIS) format spatial data set of vegetation for GUIS was created for the NPS VMI Program.

The GUIS project boundary covers an area of approximately 35,769.0 ha (88,387.2 ac). Vegetation communities at GUIS were classified and mapped by Colorado State University (CSU) under a cooperative agreement with the NPS VMI Program. CSU Mappers, ecologists, and botanists collaborated to affirm vegetation types within the U.S. National Vegetation Classification (USNVC) at GUIS and to determine how best to map them by using aerial imagery. To map the vegetation and land cover at GUIS, 38 map classes were developed. Of these 38 map classes, 34 represent natural (including ruderal) vegetation types, most of which types are recognized within the USNVC. The remaining four map classes represented non-USNVC land use cover classes (non-vegetated barren land or borrow pit, developed open space, developed low, medium, or high intensity, and water / ocean). Features were interpreted from digital aerial imagery using a heads-up digitizing approach in geographic information systems. The map classification scheme used to create the vegetation data set is designed to represent local vegetation types at the finest level possible using the National Vegetation Classification Standard (NVCS) Version 2. A minimum mapping unit of 0.5 hectares was used for all communities. Physiognomic information was also recorded. The final GUIS vegetation map consists of 1,268 polygons totaling 35,769.0 ha (88,387.2 ac). Mean polygon size is 28.2 ha (69.7 ac). Of the total area, 4,176.8 ha (10,321.1 ac) or 11.6% represent natural or ruderal vegetation map classes. Aerial Imagery that was used includes 2014 and 2016 Hexagon Imagery, 2014-2017 USDA-FSA NAIP imagery, and 2017 Post-Hurricane Nate Imagery from NOAA NGS. In addition to using aerial imagery, 2016 Topographic / Bathymetric LiDAR data available from the USACE National Coastal Mapping Program was used to analyze vegetation structure at GUIS. The NVCS standard was applied and a list of vegetation associations present was documented and compiled. The database includes tables documenting the USNVC hierarchy and allows for spatial queries that show different levels of the USNVC hierarchy associated with a vegetation polygon.

Accuracy Assessment (AA) data were collected from a total of 708 randomly allocated AA sample points in the summer of 2018. The overall accuracy of the aggregated GUIS map was 93.1%. Accuracies associated with individual map classes are presented in the final project report.

The GUIS vegetation inventory project delivers many geospatial and vegetation data products. These products consist of an in-depth project report discussing methods and results, which include descriptions and a field key to vegetation associations, map classification and map-class descriptions, and a contingency table listing AA results. The suite of products also includes a database of vegetation plots, verification sites, and AA sites; digital pictures of field sites; field data sheets; digital aerial imagery; digital maps; and a geodatabase of vegetation and land cover (map layer), field sites (vegetation plots, verification sites, and AA sites), aerial imagery index, project boundary, and metadata. All geospatial products are projected in Universal Transverse Mercator, Zone 16 North, by using the North American Datum of 1983.

The citation for the projects final report is:

Ley, M., T. Baldvins, D. Jones, H. Pilkington and K. Anderson. 2020. Vegetation classification and mapping: Gulf Islands National Seashore. Natural Resource Report NPS/XXXX/NRRâ€”2020/XXXX. National Park Service, Fort Collins, Colorado.

report.measDesc:
Topology validated using the guis_vegpoly_Topology, errors corrected, and exceptions marked using the ArcGIS Error Inspector.
Additionally, this feature class is related to the tbl_vegpoly_nlcd2001, tbl_vegpoly_nvcs2_cultural, and tbl_vegpoly_nvcs2_natural business tables through the vegpoly_nlcd2001, vegpoly_nvcs2_cultural, and vegpoly_nvcs2_natural relationship classes. They all use a one-to-many relationship.

srcExt.exDesc: Date pertains to when the images were taken, Mississippi District is 2014 30cm imagery and Florida District is 2016 15cm imagery.

dataSource.srcDesc: The U.S. National Vegetation Classification (USNVC) system was used to determine the community name and description. Version 2.03 (March 2019) was used.

srcExt.exDesc: Database accessed between May 2, 2016 and March 13, 2020.

prcStep.stepDesc: Vegetation polygons were digitized on-screen using aerial imagery. Based on field survey results, each vegetation polygon was classified to a map class associated with the lowest level of the USNVC classification. In some situations in which an USNVC classification was not present, an installation special association was created by the vegetation mapping specialist. See final report for details on field methods.
